to retain old ones, and to achieve international political tranquility through economic means. Although the negotiations began with a mixture of lofty and ignoble motives, in the end the latter predominated. The authors have drawn on archival and statistical materials in all three countries to provide a clear and detailed account of the economic context of the mid–1930s, the process of negotiations, the issues, and the political and economic significance, both then and now, of the final agreements. Their work is a valuable case–study of the problems that face any country that tries to negotiate freer trade. It is therefore full of contemporary resonance and relevance, and will be of interest to students of and specialists in modern history (European, British, and North American), international relations, and international economic policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFree tradexHistoryxCanadaxCanadaxGreat BritainxUnited States. 0aFree tradexHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aFree tradexHistoryxUnited States. 0aFree tradezCanadaxHistory. 0aFree tradezGreat BritainxHistory. 0aFree tradezUnited StatesxHistory. 4aBusiness & Economics: Economics. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science: International Relations. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aHillmer, Norman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920823040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208230/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eB